TWAS Notebook

Introduction

This notebook keeps track of information when performing the TWAS analysis. The process basically imports genotype-expression and expression-phenotype weights and performs predictions. We mainly concern TWAS study for scizophrenia data.

The relevant packages of the TWAS process are:

library('plink2R')
library("optparse")

Datasets

1. Summary GWAS statistics for szizophrenia:

sumstat = read.table("FUSION/PGC2.SCZ.sumstats",head=T,as.is=T)

This file is provided by PCG. The summary statustics maintains the basic information of scizophrenia-related loci and associated allele information. The basic property of the file is:

dim(sumstat)
[1] 1083014       6
head(sumstat)

This dataframe contains information on 1083014 SNPs. It has 6 columns containing the following information:

SNP A1 A2 Z
SNP id Major Allele Minor Allele z-score of the linear regression coefficient, \(\frac{\beta}{\sigma_\beta}\), signed with A1

We can obtain a manhattan plot by using this data:

plot(sumstat$Z)

The data has not been pruned or threshoded. We can see high polygenicity from the graph.

2. LD reference data

chromosome = 22
genos = read_plink(paste('FUSION/LDREF/1000G.EUR.',chromosome,sep=''),impute="avg")

The genos data is in PLINK format. For each chromosome, it contains three different objects: bed, fam and bim.

2.1 bed (PLINK binary biallelic genotype table)
dim(genos$bed)
[1]   489 17489
head(genos$bed[,1:8])
                rs9617528 rs4911642 rs7287144 rs5748662 rs5994034 rs4010554 rs4010558 rs3954571
HG00096:HG00096         0         0         1         1         0         1         1         2
HG00097:HG00097         0         0         0         0         1         0         0         1
HG00099:HG00099         0         0         1         1         0         1         1         1
HG00101:HG00101         1         1         1         2         0         1         1         1
HG00102:HG00102         0         1         1         1         0         1         1         0
HG00103:HG00103         0         0         1         1         0         1         1         1

This file stores the major allele frequency of each locus for the samples. This file contains 17489 SNPs for the 22nd chromosome and 489 European samples.

2.2 bim (PLINK extended MAP file)
dim(genos$bim)
[1] 17489     6
head(genos$bim)

This dataframe contains information of the corresponding SNPs. It has 6 columns containing the following information:

V1 V2 V3 V4 V5 V6
chromosome number SNP id SNP position base pair coordinate Allele 1 Allele 2

Note that the allele 1 and allele 2 are not necessarily major and minor. So the files must be adjusted according to the summary statistics file.

2.3 fam (PLINK sample information file)
dim(genos$fam)
[1] 489   6
head(genos$fam)

This dataset contains the family relations data for the 489 samples. This is not relevant to our analysis and many relational data are missing.

3. Weight Data

wgtlist = read.table('FUSION/WEIGHTS/GTEx.Whole_Blood.pos',head=T,as.is=T)
dim(wgtlist)
[1] 2057    5
head(wgtlist)

This is the genotype-expression data for whole-blood tissues provided by GTEx. The file gives us a list of different weight files tagged by their respective chromosome.

We take a specific wgt file for our example.

wgt.file = paste("FUSION/WEIGHTS","/",wgtlist$WGT[1],sep='')
load(wgt.file)

Loading the file gives us a wgt.matrix as well as a snps dataset.
